  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Brandon Lowe's Ninth-Inning Homer Completes Pittsburgh Comeback",
    "subheadline": "Pittsburgh Pirates rallies past Oakland Athletics, PIT 6, ATH 5.",
    "lead_angle": "Brandon Lowe blasted a solo home run in the top of the ninth inning, lifting the Pittsburgh Pirates to a narrow 6-5 victory over the Oakland Athletics Tuesday night at Sutter Health Park. The Athletics, holding a 4-0 lead after the first frame, watched their early advantage vanish as Pittsburgh rallied late. Mason Montgomery earned the win for the Pirates, while Elvis Alvarado took the loss for Oakland. Gregory Soto collected the save.\n\nOakland’s early burst saw Zack Gelof connect for a two-run homer in the opening inning, part of a four-run explosion against Pittsburgh’s starter. But the Pirates chipped away, and the game flipped in the seventh. Oakland held a 5-3 edge before Ryan O'Hearn singled and Tyler Callihan followed with a base hit. Bryan Reynolds then launched his second home run of the night, a two-run shot that tied the score at five and erased Oakland's final cushion.\n\nReynolds' bat proved Pittsburgh's most consistent weapon, as he finished 4-for-5, drilling two home runs and driving in three runs. His relentless production guided the comeback from an early four-run deficit. This critical road win tightens the National League playoff picture for Pittsburgh, signaling their resolve in a season fraught with important contests.",
    "reason": "A 4-run comeback is the day's best storyline — resilience over résumé."
